x4freetext: T(p,n)3He. The maximum neutron energy: ~4.2 MeV
Spread in the energy of the neutrons due to slowing
down of the protons in the target and the divergence
of the neutron beam was estimated to be ~200 keV.
The uranium target was prepared by electrospraying
about 300 microgram of U-235 over an area of 1 sq cm
on to a VYNS foil coated with a thin layer of gold.
The thickness of the VYNS foil and the gold layer was
estimated to be about 10 and 15 microgram/cm**2
The uranium foil and three identical solid-
state detectors of the diffused-junction type were
Each detector had a resistivity of 5500 ohm-cm, window
thickness of less than 1 micron of silicon, and a
sensitive depth of about 160 micron and was operated
The distance between the surface of one of the
detectors (referred to as common detector) and the
foil was about 0.2 cm so that most of the fragments
emitted in the backward hemisphere were detected by
At each of the angles of 0 and 90 deg. with the
incident direction the fragments were detected with
The divergence of the incident neutron beam was
The number of fission fragments detected by the common
detector was about 40/min and that detected by each of
the 0 and 90 deg. detectors was about 3/min.
